                                                <p> <hi rend="initialcap">C</hi>ASE.&#8212;<name type="person">Sergeant George B. Merchant</name>, <name type="organization">Co. K, 4th
                                                                Ohio Volunteers</name>, aged 33 years, received at the
                                                  battle of <name type="BATTLE" key="250"><choice><orig>Spottsylvania</orig><reg>Spotsylvania</reg></choice>, Virginia</name>, <date type="injury" when="1864-05-10">May 10, 1864</date>, a
                                                  gunshot wound of neck, with fracture of inferior
                                                  maxilla. He was admitted to <name type="hospital" key="162">Douglas Hospital</name>,
                                                                Washington, on <date type="admit" when="1864-05-13">May 13th, 1864</date>. General health
                                                                good. Secondary h&#230;morrhage occurred, to the
                                                  amount of eighteen fluid ounces, probably from
                                                  internal maxilla. On <date type="operation" when="1864-05-15">May 15th</date> the right common
                                                                carotid was ligated by <name type="person" key="200">Assistant Surgeon William
                                                                  Thomson</name>, <name type="organization" key="190">U. S. A.</name>  On <date type="operation" when="1864-05-30">May 30th</date>, it was again
                                                  ligated. On May 31st, ligature came away. He
                                                  recovered, and was returned to duty on <date type="duty" when="1864-06-19">June 19th,
                                                    1864</date>. The case is reported by the operator. The
                                                  patient is a pensioner. <name type="person">Examiner L. M. Whiting</name>
                                                  reports, <date type="pension" when="1864-09-20">September 20th, 1864</date>, that more than half
                                                  of the ramus of the right side of the lower jaw
                                                  is gone, and that there is very limited use of the
                                                  right arm, owing to some injury during the ligation. </p>
                                                
